# Source Discovery

{% include "runtime/partial/step_retry_context.md.j2" %}

Read only the current `input.json`, its generated row schemas, sibling `chart.schema.json`, sibling `state.sqlite3` through `brand-size-chart-source-discovery-state`, and declared evidence and chart artifacts. `state.json` is runtime-owned: do not read, write, or infer domain data from it.

`workflow_input.prompt_scope.product_type_request_list` is ordered. Process each requested product completely before the next one. Derive the applicable sex branches semantically from the shared product-search contract; Python does not classify products or sexes.

{% include "partial/source_type_contract.md.j2" %}

{% include "partial/product_search_sex_contract.md.j2" %}

{% include "partial/market_selection_contract.md.j2" %}

Persist every query, URL, relation, physical table row, chart, and evidence before continuing. Use only this state command for SQLite reads and writes:

```text
brand-size-chart-source-discovery-state {{ input_path }} {initialize|upsert|get|list|list-prefix|delete} ...
```

Pass exactly one schema-valid row to each `upsert` operation through standard input. Upsert a `pending` product/sex worklist row immediately before its search, then terminalize that same `(product_type, sex)` row as `searched` or `rejected` before starting another worklist row. A searched worklist row needs at least one opened URL relation. Non-product-scoped sources must not create product/sex worklist or relation rows.

Search every allowed browser-visible source surface: tables, text, tabs, modals, widgets, PDFs, images, help content, questions and answers, and linked assets. Save evidence in `evidence_write_target.filesystem_path` and reference it only through normalized paths below `evidence_write_target.artifact_path`. A request or product branch selects a boundary to inspect; it never provides table identity.

After inspecting a concrete physical table, derive `size_group_key`, `market_scope_key`, and `source_title` only from its visible heading and scope. Never derive them from the search request, product name, page category, source type, or brand. Write the chart before its matching table row:

```text
brand-size-chart-source-discovery-chart-write {{ input_path }} <size_group_key> <market_scope_key>
```

Supply one `BrandSizeChart` object through standard input. Then upsert the matching `source_table` row as `candidate` or `market_conflict`. A chart identity is exactly `(size_group_key, market_scope_key)`; do not parse chart filenames to recover identity.

After browser discovery, reread only SQLite, charts, and evidence. Finalize each `size_group_key` with the shared market ladder: upsert the selected row of the first available verified tier as `accepted`, and upsert every non-winning candidate, including lower-tier candidates, as `market_filtered`. When tier-5 candidates differ, upsert every conflicting candidate as terminal `market_conflict`; do not select an arbitrary locale or treat the group as no-table. Leave no `candidate` row. `market_conflict` is terminal data, not a correction failure. Return `BrowserActionResult` only after every current row and chart meets the terminal contract.

On retry, reuse valid current rows and charts. Change only feedback-named or incomplete rows; do not recreate valid artifacts or invent alternate identity paths.

